<span id="freeTextContainer8111151518140674939">The Sudanese narrator of this novel returns after seven years study in England. He is received warmly. Bint Majzoub put it to him in her peculiar earthy fashion, â€œWe were afraid youâ€™d bring back with you an uncircumcised infidel for a wife.â€<br/><br/>He brings instead a developing awareness for Sudan in its post-colonial state, and for men like himself and the enigmatic Moustafa Saâ€™eed who have tasted both lives. He sees a Sudan where the British left because they had no need to stay:<br/><br/><i>Be sure, though, that</i></span>
  <span id="freeText8111151518140674939" style="display:none">The Sudanese narrator of this novel returns after seven years study in England. He is received warmly. Bint Majzoub put it to him in her peculiar earthy fashion, â€œWe were afraid youâ€™d bring back with you an uncircumcised infidel for a wife.â€<br /><br />He brings instead a developing awareness for Sudan in its post-colonial state, and for men like himself and the enigmatic Moustafa Saâ€™eed who have tasted both lives. He sees a Sudan where the British left because they had no need to stay:<br /><br /><i>Be sure, though, that they will direct our affairs from afar. This is because they have left behind people who think as they do.</i><br /><br />Andâ€¦<br /><br /><i>The schools were started so as to teach us to say â€˜Yesâ€™ in their language.</i><br /><br />What was also imported was â€œthe germ of the greatest European violence, as seen on the Somme and at Verdun, the like of which the world has never previously known, the germ of a deadly disease that struck them more than a thousand years ago.â€<br /><br />Yes, history repeats. The Romans invaded Britain. Britain would, in turn, move south. Rinse, repeat. Presidents should read this.<br /><br />A love story follows the narratorâ€™s observations. Actually, love <i>stories</i>. They are not sentimental and probably allegorical.<br /><br /><i>Love? Love does not do this. This is hatred.</i><br /><br />So this book is both a warning and a blues.<br /></span>
