    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_1846116362" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1846116362" />
    <a title="Missy J" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/7406091-missy-j"><img alt="Missy J" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1481102743p2/7406091.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1846116362?book_show_action=true">Dec 23, 2016</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Missy J" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Missy J" href="/user/show/7406091-missy-j">Missy J</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780435913533" href="/book/show/6335729-season-of-migration-to-the-north">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/7406091-missy-j?shelf=2016-books">2016-books</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/7406091-missy-j?shelf=africa-related">africa-related</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/7406091-missy-j?shelf=greater-middle-east">greater-middle-east</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1846116362" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer12302959862143619860"><blockquote>
  <i>&quot;By the standards of the European industrial world we are poor peasants, but when I embrace grandfather I experience a sense of richness as though I am a note in the heartbeats of the very universe.&quot; </i>
</blockquote> Excellent writing! My reading of books translated from Arabic to English is severely limited. This year I read Sinan Antoon&apos;s <a href='https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/16073290.The_Corpse_Washer' title='The Corpse Washer by Sinan Antoon' rel='nofollow noopener'>The Corpse Washer</a> and found it lyrical in a phenomenal way. Tayeb Salih&apos;s &quot;Season of Migration to the North&quot; is equally very lyrical and evocative. Even though it is a s</span>
  <span id="freeText12302959862143619860" style="display:none"><blockquote>
  <i>"By the standards of the European industrial world we are poor peasants, but when I embrace grandfather I experience a sense of richness as though I am a note in the heartbeats of the very universe." </i>
</blockquote> Excellent writing! My reading of books translated from Arabic to English is severely limited. This year I read Sinan Antoon's <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/16073290.The_Corpse_Washer" title="The Corpse Washer by Sinan Antoon" rel="nofollow noopener">The Corpse Washer</a> and found it lyrical in a phenomenal way. Tayeb Salih's "Season of Migration to the North" is equally very lyrical and evocative. Even though it is a short book, it leaves the reader pondering. I feel inadequate to write a proper review for this book. Definitely plan to read this in the future again.<br /><br />The narrator in this novel is nameless. He returns to his village along the Nile river in the northern part of the newly independent Sudan after studying in England for seven years. Not much has changed in his village, except that a new, mysterious stranger named Mustafa Sa'eed has joined the village during his absence. Mustafa farms and lives with his wife and two sons, when on a drunken night the narrator catches him reciting a poem in English!<br /><br />Mustafa's story is extreme. I don't want to spoil the story but despite his brilliant mind in securing a scholarship to study in England, Mustafa engages in a lot stormy love affairs with British women that all end in tragedy and horror. This postcolonial work of fiction examines not only the power structure between the colonizer and the colonized. It also includes gender relations, be it in liberal England or in patriarchal Sudan. <br /><br />Call it a lie, a mirage or a phantom. Or maybe even better, <b>fata morgana</b>. Mustafa seduces the British women with Oriental fantasies. <i>"I was the invader who had come from the South, and this was the icy battlefield from which I would not make a safe return. [...] For me this moment of ecstasy is worth the whole life."</i> <br /><br />Throughout the novel, the author makes smart use of adjectives and nouns referring to hot and cold. Next time, I need to pay more attention to that. The depiction of Islam in this story is also noteworthy. At that time, the villagers didn't mind mixing Islam with their local customs (we find them drinking not a small amount of alcohol throughout the novel). In the end, I couldn't help but draw parallels between Mustafa's first marriage and what happened to Hosna. Just like the Nile River flows northwards, the influence that colonialism had on both the colonizer and the colonized becomes ubiquitous and its subsequent collision inevitable.</span>
  <a data-text-id="12302959862143619860" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


