  <span id="freeText7976811136237501986" style="display:none">This book did a really good job describing colonialism and the cultural and emotional effect it has on the citizens of a country. Even though this seems to be the main theme of the book, it is just one of the many layers of the complexity of the overall story, which describes Mustafa Saidâ€™s almost sadistic urge to â€œconquer Englandâ€ through his sexual adventures with British women. After a turbulent period in England, which ends in murder and a prison sentence, he returns to his homeland in Sudan, which is where the narrator meets him and explores Mustafaâ€™s complex personality which is masked under a very simplistic and mellow demeanour. Personally, my favourite elements of the book were the way life in a Sudanese village is described in all itsâ€™ oriental/traditional simplicity, and the beautifully descriptive literary style of Tayeb Saleh which leaves the reader wanting to read more and see what happens next. Definitely worth the read, and it left me curious about reading more books by the author. </span>
